      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah that makes sense. so it's basically like the subject is just lurking in the background instead of being front and center. if i have a long paragraph where i keep doing that, does it eventually start to feel like the real meaning is just being hidden or lost? how can i make sure the reader doesn't lose track of who is actually doing the work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a great way to think about it. When you're using passive voice excessively, it can create a sense of detachment, making it feel like the subject is just a spectator, rather than the protagonist of the story. And if that's the case, the reader might start to wonder who's really in charge, and what's really going on.\n\nTo avoid this, try to identify the most important actions in your paragraph and rephrase those sentences in the active voice. Ask yourself, \"What's the main event here?\" or \"Who's the one doing the heavy lifting?\" By putting the doer of the action front and center, you'll make it clear who's responsible for the outcome.\n\nFor example, if you have a paragraph like this:\n\n\"The data was collected, analyzed, and interpreted by the research team. The results were then presented to the study's participants, who were informed about the study's findings.\"\n\nYou could rephrase it to:\n\n\"The research team collected, analyzed, and interpreted the data. The team then presented the results to the study's participants, who were informed about the study's findings.\"\n\nBy rephrasing the sentences in the active voice, you've made it clear that the research team is the one doing",
      "source": "target",
